{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:01:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:01:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18031"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18031"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.48,0.05,0.03,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73321"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10745"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58792"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6776"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25073"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73321"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vertebral levels corresponds to the location of the cricoid cartilage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C4","C6","C8","C7","C5"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cricoid cartilage is a ring-shaped structure located in the neck and is the only complete ring of cartilage around the trachea. It is situated at the level of the \u003Cstrong\u003EC6\u003C/strong\u003E vertebra. This anatomical landmark is important for various medical procedures, including tracheostomy and intubation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC4\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EC5\u003C/strong\u003E are higher in the neck and correspond to the level of the thyroid cartilage and the hyoid bone, respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC7\u003C/strong\u003E is lower in the neck and is typically associated with the vertebra prominens, which is the most prominent cervical vertebra.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC8\u003C/strong\u003E is not a vertebral level; the cervical spine consists of only seven vertebrae, and C8 refers to a cervical nerve root rather than a vertebra.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cricoid cartilage is located at the C6 vertebral level.","Understanding the anatomical landmarks of the neck is crucial for procedures such as tracheostomy and intubation."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58792"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18031"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisio